       \n        # Directions for moving up, down, left, right\n        directions = [(-1, 0), (1, 0), (0, -1), (0, 1)]\n        distance = -1\n        \n        # Perform BFS from all land cells simultaneously\n        while queue:\n            distance += 1\n            for _ in range(len(queue)):\n                x, y = queue.popleft()\n                for dx, dy in directions:\n                    nx, ny = x + dx, y + dy\n                    if 0 <= nx < n and 0 <= ny < n and grid[nx][ny] == 0:\n                        grid[nx][ny] = 1  # Mark the cell as visited by setting it to land\n                        queue.append((nx, ny))\n        \n        return distance\n```\n\nThis solution uses a Breadth-First Search (BFS) approach to find the maximum distance from any water cell to the nearest land cell. It starts by adding all land cells to a queue and then performs a BFS, marking visited water cells as land to avoid revisiting them. The BFS ensures that the shortest path (Manhattan distance) to any land cell is found for each water cell, and the maximum of these distances is returned.", "estimated_date": 1566086400000}